name: carolina-sandhills-national-wildlife-refuge-pine-barrens-treefrog-survey-data-report-for-2
notes: The Pine Barrens Treefrog (Hyla andersonii Baird) is listed as a threatened species in need of management in South Carolina. Carolina Sandhills National Wildlife Refuge supports numerous colonies of the Pine Barrens Treefrog and is home to the second largest concentration of this species in the state. A goal outlined in the Comprehensive Conservation Plan for the Carolina Sandhills National Wildlife Refuge is that the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service (USFWS) would conduct a baseline population survey of Pine Barrens Treefrogs in appropriate habitat (seeps), coordinate with the SC Department of Natural Resources (SCDNR) & volunteers, and conduct surveys to discern population trends and assess effects of habitat management. The USFWS and SCDNR collected data for the first year of the survey during FY2012. This internship project collected survey data during FY2013. The survey utilized Wildlife Acoustics, Inc. Songmeter Model SM2 and SM2+ bioacoustic monitoring equipment to survey the presence/absence of anuran (i.e., frog and toad) species during the period of March 14, 2013 - August 31, 2013. Data was analyzed utilizing Wildlife Acoustics, Inc. Song Scope Analysis Software. In total 16 sites were surveyed and 509 hours of data was collected and analyzed. Pine Barrens Treefrogs were documented at 9 of the 16 sites surveyed. In an effort to better assess population trends, the North American Amphibian Monitoring Program (NAAMP) unified protocol was utilized to assign an index value to recordings containing Pine Barrens Treefrog vocalizations. Average NAAMP index values ranged from 0-2.40. In addition to the Pine Barrens Treefrog, the presence of the following anuran species was documented during the survey: Cricket Frog (Acris sp.), Spring Peeper (Pseudacris crucifer), Green Treefrog (Hyla cinerea), Barking Treefrog (Hyla gratiosa), Pine Woods Treefrog (Hyla femoralis), Copeâ€™s Gray Treefrog (Hyla chrysoscelis), Southern Toad (Bufo terrestris), Bullfrog (Rana catesbeiana), Green Frog (Rana clamitans), Carpenter Frog (Rana virgatipes), Southern Leopard Frog (Rana sphenocephala), and Eastern Narrowmouth Toad (Gastrophryne carolinensis). Of special interest was the suspected presence of the River Frog (Rana heckscheri). This species had not been previously documented at the refuge and is thought to have been extirpated in North Carolina. Water chemistry data was also collected at 7 sites during the survey period to provide baseline water quality information for the refuge and to further investigate what constitutes suitable breeding habitat for the Pine Barrens Treefrog.
